    <abstract>
        Sun Baotian 孫 葆田 (1840-1911), who was a local official in Shandong, gives the fullest details . In his Shandong jinshi zhi 山東金石誌 (Epigraphic Records of Shandong) of 1911, 
        he records twelve sections of the Lankāvatara sutra version B and transcribes each of them in full. His layout reproduces the numbers of columns and characters in each column. 
        He begins with B28 as the most imposing section and describes the position of each stone in relation to this stone and to others, but he fails to understand the sequence, 
        in which the stones have to be read, because he does not recognize the sutra text. Although he observes that the characters of A5 are smaller than those of other sections, 
        he does not realize that two versions of the same text exist on Mount Gang. He records five characters in passages whose whereabouts are no longer known today. (LL)</abstract>
